<section class="card">
  <h2>About Winter Squash</h2>

  <p class="tagline">
    Long-season warm crop—requires sustained heat and finishes before frost.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Winter squash is frost-tender and can be killed at 32°F (0°C).</strong>
    In a typical year (1991–2020 climate normals at the 50% probability level), winter squash viability depends on planting after last frost, accumulating sufficient Growing Degree Days (GDD), and fully maturing fruit before first fall frost.
  </p>

  <p>
    Compared to zucchini or cucumbers, winter squash typically requires a longer heat runway.
    In short seasons, variety selection and early growth speed determine whether fruit reaches full maturity and cures properly before frost.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Planning Reference</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Direct sow:</strong> 2–4 weeks after last frost (warm soil required)</li>
    <li><strong>Indoor start (optional):</strong> 3–4 weeks before transplant window</li>
    <li><strong>Days to maturity:</strong> 80–110+ days (variety-dependent)</li>
    <li><strong>Frost tolerance:</strong> None (killed at 32°F / 0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine muted">
    These are baseline ranges. Longer-maturity types (e.g., large pumpkins) require extended heat accumulation.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Temperature & Soil Requirements</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Minimum soil temperature:</strong> ~60–65°F (16–18°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Optimal growth:</strong> 70–90°F (21–32°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Slow growth:</strong> Below ~60°F (16°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Freeze damage:</strong> 32°F (0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Winter squash stalls in cool soil and cool nights.
    Early planting into marginal conditions often delays flowering and reduces maturity buffer before first frost.
  </p>

  <p class="fine">
    For frost probability context, see:
    <a href="/guides/average-frost-date-vs-actual-weather/">Average frost date vs actual weather</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Typical GDD Requirement</h2>

  <p><strong>Base temperature:</strong> 50°F (10°C)</p>
  <p><strong>Approximate GDD needed:</strong> ~1,500–2,500+ GDD (base 50), depending on type and fruit size</p>

  <p>
    Winter squash is strongly heat-dependent. Large-fruited varieties require substantially more accumulated heat than small-fruited or early types.
    In cool summers, labeled “90-day” varieties may mature later than expected if GDD accumulation is weak.
  </p>

  <p class="fine muted" style="margin-top:14px;">
    GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Use the GDD Planner</a>
  </div>

  <p class="fine">
    For the combined frost + heat framework, see:
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How frost dates and Growing Degree Days work together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Minimum Frost-Free Days</h2>

  <p>
    Most winter squash varieties require <strong>80–110+ frost-free days</strong>.
    Larger pumpkin types may require even longer.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short seasons, selecting early or compact varieties is critical to preserving margin before first frost.
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Check Your Frost-Free Season</a>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short-Season Viability Flag</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Good choice under 100 days?</strong> Only with early varieties</li>
    <li><strong>Risky under 90 days?</strong> Often, unless summer heat is strong and season starts early</li>
    <li><strong>Needs season extension?</strong> Sometimes helpful (black mulch, warm microclimates)</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>First Frost Sensitivity</h2>

  <p>
    Winter squash has no frost tolerance buffer. A freeze at 32°F (0°C) can damage vines and fruit.
    First frost is a hard maturity cutoff.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Early-Maturing Strategy</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Select early or small-fruited varieties in tight frost windows</li>
    <li>Start indoors briefly to preserve runway (avoid root disturbance)</li>
    <li>Plant in full sun with heat-retaining soil surfaces</li>
    <li>Avoid shaded or wind-exposed microclimates that reduce effective GDD</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planning Model</h2>

  <p class="muted">
    Frost → Season Length → GDD → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin
  </p>

  <p>
    In a typical year, winter squash is viable when your frost-free window and seasonal heat budget exceed the crop’s maturity requirement.
    When buffer is thin, delayed planting or weak summer heat commonly pushes maturity too close to first frost.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <h3>Can winter squash survive frost?</h3>
  <p>
    No. Winter squash is frost-sensitive and can be damaged or killed at 32°F (0°C).
  </p>

  <h3>Why didn’t my squash fully mature?</h3>
  <p>
    Most often, the variety required more GDD than your climate provided, or early growth was slowed by cool conditions.
  </p>

  <h3>Are small squash varieties better for short seasons?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. Smaller-fruited and early-maturing types typically require fewer frost-free days and less accumulated heat.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Use 32°F (0°C) as the frost boundary (50% probability, 1991–2020 normals).</li>
    <li>Winter squash is frost-sensitive and strongly heat-dependent.</li>
    <li>Typical requirement: 80–110+ days, ~1,500–2,500+ GDD (base 50).</li>
    <li>Model viability using frost window + seasonal heat budget + variety requirement + risk margin.</li>
  </ul>
</section>